# Phase 7 — App Assembly, Routing, Dashboard & Security Hardening

> **Copy-paste this entire block into your engineering AI.**
> **Prerequisite: Phase 6 verification must be 100% complete.**

---

## 1. Why This Phase Exists

All three capabilities are built. The domain is correct. The tests pass per-phase. But a collection of correct components is not the same as a correct system. This phase assembles those components into an application the owner can actually use, verifies that the constitutional constraints hold across the entire codebase (not just within each phase's scope), and explicitly marks what remains to be done for native Android Keystore integration.

This phase also performs the final security audit — the grep-based checks that prove the assembly did not accidentally introduce cross-layer pollution, hardcoded URLs, plaintext secrets, or confirmation semantics.

---

## 2. Constraints — Read Before Writing Anything

### Constraint 2.1: Verify the Whole Before Adding the Assembly Layer
Before writing any new code, run the full security checklist in Section 5. If any check fails, fix the violation first. Adding routing and navigation on top of a broken foundation will make the violations harder to find, not easier.

### Constraint 2.2: The Global Navigator Key Is an Architectural Compromise
The `GlobalKey<NavigatorState>` in `main.dart` is necessary for showing the 2FA approval dialog from inside `Auth2faFcmHandler`, which has no `BuildContext`. This is a pragmatic coupling between the infrastructure layer and the presentation layer that violates strict Clean Architecture. It is acceptable here because:
- The alternative (a custom navigation event bus) adds significant complexity for one use case
- The dependency is one-directional: the FCM handler depends on a global navigator key, not on any widget
- It is documented as `// TODO(phase-7): extract to a NavigationService abstraction`

Do not expand this pattern. The navigator key must be used only for the 2FA dialog. OTP and Payment Observation do not show a dialog — they run silently.

### Constraint 2.3: The Dashboard Is a Status Display, Not a Control Panel
The dashboard shows which systems are paired and which capabilities each system has. It does NOT show: current challenge status, OTP log entries, payment observation state. Those are runtime events handled invisibly by the FCM handlers.

The dashboard has one active control: an unpair button (with confirmation) per system. No other controls are needed. Adding more controls risks turning the "dumb executor" into a "smart agent" — violating Axiom 1.

### Constraint 2.4: The Initial Route Is Determined at Runtime by the Registry
On cold start, if `PairedSystemRegistry.all` is empty → route to the pairing page. If any paired system exists → route to the dashboard. This logic lives in a single function in `main.dart`, not in a Cubit or use case. It is a presentation routing decision, not a business rule.

### Constraint 2.5: Platform Channel Stubs Must Be Explicitly Marked
Every Android native feature that is not yet implemented must have a `// TODO(phase-7-android):` comment in the calling Dart code. This phase collects all such TODOs in one place. The engineering AI responsible for the native Android layer will search for these markers.

The complete list of unimplemented native features at the end of Phase 7:
- Android Keystore hardware-backed signing (Kotlin `MethodChannel`)
- `SmsManager` dual-SIM sending with `sentIntent`/`deliveredIntent` (Kotlin `MethodChannel`)
- `BroadcastReceiver` for `SMS_RECEIVED` → `EventChannel`
- `KeyguardManager.isDeviceSecure()` check for Stop Condition SC-10

### Constraint 2.6: No Stop Condition May Remain Unverified
Stop Conditions from `AGENT_BEHAVIOR/stop_conditions.md` must each have a verification: either a unit test that proves the condition causes the correct early exit, or a structural grep check that proves the enforcement code exists. SC-10 (no screen lock) is an exception — it requires native Android and is deferred with a `// TODO(phase-7-android):` marker.

