## 3. What to Build

### Step 1: Pre-Assembly Security Verification
Run all checks in Section 5 before writing code. Fix any failure before proceeding.

### Step 2: Runtime Permission Handler
Create `lib/shared/infrastructure/permission_handler_service.dart`.
Add `permission_handler: ^11.3.1` to `pubspec.yaml`.
Static method `Future<Map<Permission, bool>> requestAll()` — requests SMS, phone, camera permissions and returns a map of permission → granted status. Called once in `main()` after `setupDependencies()`.
Document: if SMS permission is denied, the OTP gateway capability will silently fail when attempting to send. The agent does not block startup for permission denial — it reports the failure at dispatch time.

### Step 3: Global Navigator Key
In `lib/main.dart`, declare: `final GlobalKey<NavigatorState> navigatorKey = GlobalKey<NavigatorState>();`
Pass it to `MaterialApp(navigatorKey: navigatorKey, ...)`.
Document with: `// TODO(phase-7): extract to NavigationService to reduce coupling`

### Step 4: Update `Auth2faFcmHandler`
Use the global navigator key to push the `ChallengeApprovalDialog` as a `MaterialPageRoute` with `fullscreenDialog: true`. Wrap the dialog in `BlocProvider.value(value: cubit, ...)`.

### Step 5: 2FA Approval Dialog
Build `lib/presentation/auth_2fa/widgets/challenge_approval_dialog.dart`.
Rules:
- Wrap entire dialog in `PopScope(canPop: false)` — no back-button dismissal. The owner must tap APPROVE or REJECT.
- Display: `contextLabel`, `challengeId`, `expiresAt` (formatted). These three fields only — do not display system internals.
- Two buttons: APPROVE and REJECT. Each calls `cubit.submitDecision(AgentDecision.approve/reject)`.
- On `AuthChallengeSubmitted` state: pop the dialog.
- On `AuthChallengeError` state: pop the dialog, show a `SnackBar`.
- No auto-dismiss. No countdown timer visible in the UI (the server enforces expiry).

### Step 6: Pairing Page
Build `lib/presentation/pairing/pages/pairing_page.dart`.
States handled:
- `PairingIdle`: show "Pair with a System" button → calls `cubit.startScanning()`
- `PairingScanning`: show QR scanner (`MobileScanner`) → on detect, call `cubit.onQrScanned(rawValue)`
- `PairingTokenScanned`: show system label, capabilities list, endpoint URL, "Confirm and Pair" button → calls `cubit.confirmPairing()`
- `PairingInProgress`: show loading indicator
- `PairingSuccess`: navigate to `/dashboard`
- `PairingError`: show `SnackBar` with message, return to `Idle`

### Step 7: Dashboard Page
Build `lib/presentation/dashboard/pages/dashboard_page.dart`.
Reads `PairedSystemRegistry.all` directly from `GetIt` (not from a Cubit — the registry is already loaded).
Shows a list of paired systems with: system label, agent ID, granted capabilities.
Each item has an unpair icon button. Tapping it shows a confirmation dialog ("Are you sure you want to unpair [label]?"). On confirmation, calls `PairingCubit.unpair(systemId)` and updates the list.
FAB navigates to `/pair`.

### Step 8: Routing in `main.dart`
Replace the placeholder `home:` with named routes:
- `/` → determine initial page at runtime (pairing or dashboard)
- `/pair` → `PairingPage` wrapped in `BlocProvider`
- `/dashboard` → `DashboardPage`

Add `_resolveInitialPage()` that checks `PairedSystemRegistry.all.isEmpty`.

### Step 9: Stop Condition Audit
For each Stop Condition, verify enforcement exists:

| Stop Condition | Enforcement Location | Verification Method |
|---|---|---|
| SC-1: FCM from unknown system | `FcmMessageRouter.route()` | Unit test (Phase 3) |
| SC-2: FCM for ungranted capability | `FcmMessageRouter.route()` | Unit test (Phase 3) |
| SC-3: Command fetch fails | Cubit emits `Error` state | Unit test per capability (Phases 4–6) |
| SC-4: QR payload invalid | `parsePairingToken()` → `Left` | Unit test (Phase 2) |
| SC-5: Non-PENDING command | Status check in use cases | Unit test (Phases 4–6) |
| SC-6: Signing fails | Use cases return `Left` on failure | Unit test (Phases 4–6) |
| SC-7: Server rejects (HTTP 401) | Repo impls return `Left` | Manual integration test |
| SC-8: Empty OTP body | Add `assert(messageBody.isNotEmpty)` in `OtpDispatchCommand` | Grep for assert |
| SC-9: Parse returns null fields | Null-field report submitted | Unit test (Phase 6) |
| SC-10: No screen lock | `// TODO(phase-7-android):` marker | Native Android phase |

---

## 4. Key Design Decisions to Understand

**Why is the dashboard stateless (no Cubit)?**
The dashboard reads from `PairedSystemRegistry` which is already loaded and updated by the pairing/unpairing use cases. There is no async data loading needed at display time. A stateless widget reading from a singleton registry is simpler and less error-prone than a Cubit that mirrors the same data.

**Why does the approval dialog pop on error, rather than staying open?**
If submission fails, the challenge is still `pending` on the server (unless the server timed it out). A new FCM push would arrive and open a new dialog. Keeping the error dialog open would block the new one. Popping and showing a SnackBar allows recovery.

